<div id="review_3074941875" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3074941875" />
    <a title="Debbie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41918078-debbie"><img alt="Debbie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594390250p2/41918078.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3074941875?book_show_action=true">Dec 17, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Debbie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Debbie" href="/user/show/41918078-debbie">Debbie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9781515926948" href="/book/show/41189088-the-children-s-blizzard">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=gilded-age">gilded-age</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=disaster">disaster</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=2021-reads">2021-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=nature">nature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=informative">informative</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=farm-life">farm-life</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=microhistory">microhistory</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41918078-debbie?shelf=american-midwest">american-midwest</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3074941875" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8275997471068880822"><b>I wanted to read this book because...</b><br/>I really enjoyed <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5300.Laura_Ingalls_Wilder' title='Laura Ingalls Wilder' rel='nofollow noopener'>Laura Ingalls Wilder</a>&apos;s book <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8282.The_Long_Winter__Little_House___6_' title='The Long Winter (Little House, #6) by Laura Ingalls Wilder' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Long Winter</a>; therefore, I wanted to check out the nonfiction version of the killer blizzard of January 12, 1888.<br/><b>NOTE:</b> I was mistaken! <br/>From this particular book, I learned that <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8282.The_Long_Winter__Little_House___6_' title='The Long Winter (Little House, #6) by Laura Ingalls Wilder' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Long Winter</a> is actually &quot;The Snow Winter&quot; of 1880-81 that affected a large part of northern and central U.S. beginning in October 1880, with blizzards occurring almost nonstop until April 1881! (Oops!😬)<br/><br/><b>Positives:</b><br/>1. author <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/92055.David_Laskin' title='David Laskin' rel='nofollow noopener'>David Laskin</a></span>
  <span id="freeText8275997471068880822" style="display:none"><b>I wanted to read this book because...</b><br />I really enjoyed <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/5300.Laura_Ingalls_Wilder" title="Laura Ingalls Wilder" rel="nofollow noopener">Laura Ingalls Wilder</a>'s book <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8282.The_Long_Winter__Little_House___6_" title="The Long Winter (Little House, #6) by Laura Ingalls Wilder" rel="nofollow noopener">The Long Winter</a>; therefore, I wanted to check out the nonfiction version of the killer blizzard of January 12, 1888.<br /><b>NOTE:</b> I was mistaken! <br />From this particular book, I learned that <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8282.The_Long_Winter__Little_House___6_" title="The Long Winter (Little House, #6) by Laura Ingalls Wilder" rel="nofollow noopener">The Long Winter</a> is actually "The Snow Winter" of 1880-81 that affected a large part of northern and central U.S. beginning in October 1880, with blizzards occurring almost nonstop until April 1881! (Oops!😬)<br /><br /><b>Positives:</b><br />1. author <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/92055.David_Laskin" title="David Laskin" rel="nofollow noopener">David Laskin</a> relates extensive background information about:<br />- the immigrants and relocators who were directly affected by this blizzard;<br />- the frequent threats of the three "prairie plagues" - fire, grasshoppers and harsh weather conditions (Bonus: Laskin does mention Wilder's book <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8282.The_Long_Winter__Little_House___6_" title="The Long Winter (Little House, #6) by Laura Ingalls Wilder" rel="nofollow noopener">The Long Winter</a>!);<br />- the atmospheric conditions that triggered this fatal storm; <br />- the role of the Signal Corps in reporting weather "indications" and the mindless bureaucracy involved;<br />- decisions made by everyone involved, including the affected children themselves; and,<br />- how frostbite and hypothermia occur;<br />2. Laskin's descriptive writing of the blizzard itself, the victims and the survivors (including various animals) was extremely graphic and quite heartbreaking; and,<br />3. I appreciated his use of analogies.<br /><br /><b>Niggles:</b><br />1. my attention would occasionally wane while listening to this audiobook during the "dry filler" portions that focused on the political bureaucracy; and,<br />2. it's <i>not</i> "the Ukraine" - it's just "Ukraine"!<br /><br />I highly recommend this book for nonfiction aficionados!</span>
  <a data-text-id="8275997471068880822" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


