<div id="review_4351125463" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4351125463" />
    <a title="Joe Krakovsky" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42636932-joe-krakovsky"><img alt="Joe Krakovsky" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1497655040p2/42636932.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4351125463?book_show_action=true">Dec 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe Krakovsky" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe Krakovsky" href="/user/show/42636932-joe-krakovsky">Joe Krakovsky</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42636932-joe-krakovsky?shelf=survival">survival</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42636932-joe-krakovsky?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4351125463" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1801753470951957167">&quot;The Children&apos;s Blizzard&quot; was a sad tale. Reading it during a cold spell really set the mood. As I read about the pioneers struggling to get their animals into shelter, I thought of our animals and wondered what I would do if the weather really, really got bad. But being as it will around 50 tomorrow, on December 14th, I wonder if there is some merit to the global warming warnings.<br/><br/>Our temperature here in central Illinois seems to fluctuate a bit, but I can&apos;t imagine walking around in a t-shirt a</span>
  <span id="freeText1801753470951957167" style="display:none">"The Children's Blizzard" was a sad tale. Reading it during a cold spell really set the mood. As I read about the pioneers struggling to get their animals into shelter, I thought of our animals and wondered what I would do if the weather really, really got bad. But being as it will around 50 tomorrow, on December 14th, I wonder if there is some merit to the global warming warnings.<br /><br />Our temperature here in central Illinois seems to fluctuate a bit, but I can't imagine walking around in a t-shirt and then seeing this cloud of snow and ice bearing down on me like a desert sandstorm or a dust bowl storm from the 1930's. That is basically what happened to these poor people. The temperature dropped fast like in that movie, "The Day After Tomorrow." When it hit, it hit hard. People got lost walking from the barn to the house because not only was the snow thick, but part of it was like pieces of sand or shards of glass. It stuck to their eyes and blinded them. People panicked. Teachers sent children home, even though they didn't have coats or boots because they knew they would eventually freeze to death when the coal ran out. This book talks about that tragedy.<br /><br />Also explained was how cold fronts form and why high- and low-pressure fronts are important. Did you know that the army Signal Corps was in charge of reporting weather 'indications?' Probably the real reason for this was to warn the farmers in the deep south. This storm was so massive that the cold front traveled all the way down through Texas and Mexico to the Gulf of Tehuantepec. Out on the plains hell froze over.<br /><br />What was very important was the explanation of the different stages of freezing to death and how to revive those suffering from hypothermia. Some of the survivors after the worst of the storm and its freezing temperatures got up from their place of shelter, took a few steps and dropped dead. Some survived, but not all.<br /><br />This book was worth reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1801753470951957167" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

