    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3093136344" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3093136344" />
    <a title="Lynn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15265939-lynn"><img alt="Lynn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1356920956p2/15265939.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3093136344?book_show_action=true">Jan 31, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lynn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lynn" href="/user/show/15265939-lynn">Lynn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780061438660" href="/book/show/7128836-the-childrens-blizzard">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15265939-lynn?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15265939-lynn?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15265939-lynn?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15265939-lynn?shelf=nook">nook</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3093136344" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4887205966505904568">This is an historical accounting of the horrific blizzard that struck the Great Plains on January 12, 1888. Known as the Schoolchildren’s blizzard because so many children died after they were let out of school early to go home during the blizzard. The storm was so severe that if you stepped a few feet out of your house, you might not find your way back home. The descriptions of the storm are beyond comprehension: fine ice that blew so hard it could almost sandblast the skin off your face, freez</span>
  <span id="freeText4887205966505904568" style="display:none">This is an historical accounting of the horrific blizzard that struck the Great Plains on January 12, 1888. Known as the Schoolchildren’s blizzard because so many children died after they were let out of school early to go home during the blizzard. The storm was so severe that if you stepped a few feet out of your house, you might not find your way back home. The descriptions of the storm are beyond comprehension: fine ice that blew so hard it could almost sandblast the skin off your face, freeze your eyes shut and clog your nose; feet and hands freezing solid; getting so turned around that you would walk miles out of your way; people freezing to death in their homes. <br /><br />The author first gets into the history of the people who settled in the Great Plains: where they came from, why they left their homes in Europe and what life was like as they settled into their new lives. He also dives deep into the science of meteorology as it existed during that time. There were long explanations about the effects of highs and lows and how they influence weather patterns. I have read about this before, in Erik Larson’s book Isaac’s Storm, and I’ll be honest: I still don’t get it. He also gets into the politics of weather forecasting of the time, and all the power struggles that went on. <br /><br />Once he gets into the description of the actual blizzard and the disaster that ensued, the book becomes compelling and horrifying. There were times I just had to close my eyes and stop reading because it was too horrific. The scenes of children dying were just beyond comprehension. The author also gets into long explanations of what freezing does to the body, down to a cellular level. At times it was TMI. <br /><br />In the aftermath of the storm, aside from the terrible losses suffered by the people, it seemed like nothing changed. Weather forecasting remained a power struggle; survivors’ stories were exploited by the press, although some did try to raise money for selected survivors; and nothing was learned or implemented to prevent another disaster. In fact, 3 months, later a Nor’easter hit NYC and crippled it, and hundreds died because there was no advance warning. <br /><br />On a personal note, January 12 is my birthday, and I felt a personal connection to this story because of it. Please note that it’s not the same year as the Children’s Blizzard! Also, I read this book during a snowstorm in the Chicago area, and I kept feeling how lucky I was: we had advance warning of the storm due to all the meteorological advances we now have; I could stock up on things that I needed before the storm; I was safe, warm and comfortable during the storm; and there was absolutely no reason to leave my home. <br /><br />This book was an interesting read, although a bit dry and technical at times. I know that Melanie Benjamin has written a book about the Children’s Blizzard and I’ll be interested to read her take on the tragedy. It will be different because she writes historical fiction, so I expect that she’ll concentrate more on the people and the emotional aspects of the events and less on the factual history. <br /><br />If you don’t mind getting a bit bogged down in some minutiae, this is a good book. I also recommend reading it during a snowstorm...it adds to the ambiance of the book. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4887205966505904568" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


