    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_511644442" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/511644442" />
    <a title="Manybooks" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2970379-manybooks"><img alt="Manybooks" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459773375p2/2970379.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/511644442?book_show_action=true">Jan 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Manybooks" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Manybooks" href="/user/show/2970379-manybooks">Manybooks</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6624971-the-children-s-blizzard">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2970379-manybooks?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2970379-manybooks?shelf=farming">farming</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2970379-manybooks?shelf=little-house-series">little-house-series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2970379-manybooks?shelf=depressing">depressing</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2970379-manybooks?shelf=book-reviews">book-reviews</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2970379-manybooks?shelf=weather">weather</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2970379-manybooks?shelf=too-much-information">too-much-information</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2970379-manybooks?shelf=dragging-writing-style">dragging-writing-style</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer511644442" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18188358548023413539">Although I do of course very much appreciate the amount of historical research David Laskin has obviously done for his featured text and that yes indeed the introduction to <u>The Children’s Blizzard</u> really does a wonderful job explaining just how devastating this 1888 Midwest blizzard was, why so many school children perished and that the often recent immigrant victims of the storm were obviously sabotaged both by shoddy and careless official weather forecasts and their own inexperience and know-h</span>
  <span id="freeText18188358548023413539" style="display:none">Although I do of course very much appreciate the amount of historical research David Laskin has obviously done for his featured text and that yes indeed the introduction to <u>The Children’s Blizzard</u> really does a wonderful job explaining just how devastating this 1888 Midwest blizzard was, why so many school children perished and that the often recent immigrant victims of the storm were obviously sabotaged both by shoddy and careless official weather forecasts and their own inexperience and know-how dealing with prairie winter weather and especially blizzard conditions that appeared quickly and dangerously (with mighty winds, frigid temperatures and blinding snow and ice continuing unabated for many many hours), for me, I really and truly have only found the just mentioned prologue, the introduction truly readable, enjoyable and engaging. <br /><br />Because while in the main text of <u>The Children’s Blizzard</u>, David Laskin does of course show much interesting and enlightening information (and not only about the 1888 blizzard and why it was such a horrible and often lethal scenario), the incredibly long set-up regarding mid to late 19th century immigration to the USA and how many newcomers were basically totally ill prepared for homesteading, for farming on the Great Plains of the United States and Canada, this really does tend to get quite dragging and tedious very quickly so that by the time David Laskin actually starts describing the so-called Children’s Blizzard itself, I was in fact so bored and so full of reading frustration and tedium that I ended up needing to skim over the rest of Larkin’s printed words, leaving me with the feeling that <u>The Children’s Blizzard</u> leaves quite a bit to be personally desired by me and is textually just not engaging and enjoyable enough to consider more than a three star ranking, and not to mention that finding out about all those unfortunate children being caught in the blizzard and freezing to death has been rather majorly depressing at best (but indeed, I will also be lowering my rating for <u>The Children’s Blizzard</u> to a high two stars, as I also and equally do think that how David Laskin depicts his researched and consulted sources is rather reader and user unfriendly and that I also am missing a separate and thematics specific bibliography with regard to <u>The Children’s Blizzard</u>).</span>
  <a data-text-id="18188358548023413539" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


