    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3882779117" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3882779117" />
    <a title="Carol" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1166663-carol"><img alt="Carol" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1277905205p2/1166663.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3882779117?book_show_action=true">Mar 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carol" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carol" href="/user/show/1166663-carol">Carol</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780060520755" href="/book/show/1611726.The_Children_s_Blizzard">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1166663-carol?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3882779117" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5266789892871537474">I have to wonder why I hadn&apos;t read this book until now. Words like gripping, tragic, horrific storm, historical, family interviews and more would be likely to put <u>The Children&apos;s Blizzard</u> on my list of must reads. Perhaps, because it was the 125th anniversary of this blizzard January 12 and 13th, it piqued my interest. <br/><br/>Any book that describes the deaths of approximately 500 persons, many of them children, a storm that is called Schoolchildren&apos;s Blizzard, can not be easy to read. Be warned that th</span>
  <span id="freeText5266789892871537474" style="display:none">I have to wonder why I hadn't read this book until now. Words like gripping, tragic, horrific storm, historical, family interviews and more would be likely to put <u>The Children's Blizzard</u> on my list of must reads. Perhaps, because it was the 125th anniversary of this blizzard January 12 and 13th, it piqued my interest. <br /><br />Any book that describes the deaths of approximately 500 persons, many of them children, a storm that is called Schoolchildren's Blizzard, can not be easy to read. Be warned that there are graphic descriptions of these deaths. <br /><br />David Laskin gives voice to the victims and survivors. This tribute to the resiliency, the struggles, the lives of these families and individuals, is what made this a powerful read for me. It is a picture of a time gone by, of immigrants, mostly Swiss-German Mennonites who emigrated to this country around 1873 for a better life and experiencing the hardships that confront them. Laskin's research is thorough using newspapers, books, and the memories and diaries of descendants, he is able to provide a compelling historical read. <br /><br />Other than the story itself, <u>The Children's Blizzard</u> prompted me to think about survival skills, not only what I would do if confronted by a storm of this magnitude, but those of life, especially during this pandemic. <br /><br />Highly recommended. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5266789892871537474" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


